<DocsLayout title="Getting Started" activeSection="getting-started">
  <h1>Getting Started</h1>

  <p>
    Flick is an internal feature flag platform. It gives your team boolean toggles,
    percentage rollouts, and group-based targeting &mdash; with SDKs that evaluate locally
    and never block your app.
  </p>

  <h2>Architecture</h2>

  <pre><code>┌──────────────┐     ┌──────────────┐     ┌──────────────┐
│  Astro UI    │────▶│  Fastify API │◀────│  MCP Server  │
│  (Dashboard) │     │  (Server)    │     │  (AI Agents) │
└──────────────┘     └──────┬───────┘     └──────────────┘
                            │
                     ┌──────┴───────┐
                     │              │
                ┌────▼────┐  ┌─────▼─────┐
                │ Postgres│  │   Redis   │
                │ (Data)  │  │  (Cache)  │
                └─────────┘  └───────────┘
                            ▲
              ┌─────────────┼─────────────┐
              │             │             │
        ┌─────▼─────┐ ┌────▼──────┐ ┌────▼──────┐
        │ TS SDK    │ │ Kotlin SDK│ │ Other SDKs│
        │ (polling) │ │ (polling) │ │  (future) │
        └───────────┘ └───────────┘ └───────────┘</code></pre>

  <h2>Key Concepts</h2>

  <h3>Gate Types</h3>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Gate</th>
        <th>Evaluation</th>
        <th>Config</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Boolean</strong></td>
        <td>Simple on/off</td>
        <td><code>{"{}"}</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Percentage</strong></td>
        <td><code>murmurhash3(flagKey + contextKey) % 100 &lt; percentage</code></td>
        <td><code>{"{ percentage, sticky }"}</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Group</strong></td>
        <td>Context attributes matched against group rules</td>
        <td><code>{"{}"}</code> (groups linked via <code>flag_groups</code>)</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Environments</h3>
  <p>
    Flags have per-environment configuration. A flag might be enabled in <code>dev</code>,
    disabled in <code>staging</code>, and rolled out to 25% in <code>production</code>.
    The <code>flag_environments</code> table is the core join &mdash; flags have no state
    without an environment.
  </p>

  <h3>Groups</h3>
  <p>
    Groups are named sets of targeting rules. Rules within a group are AND'd.
    Multiple groups attached to a flag are OR'd. This lets you build complex targeting
    like "Pro users in the US OR beta testers".
  </p>

  <h2>Quick Start</h2>

  <h3>1. Create a flag</h3>
  <p>
    Open the <a href="/">dashboard</a>, click <strong>New Flag</strong>, give it a key
    like <code>new-checkout</code>, and choose a gate type.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Enable it in an environment</h3>
  <p>
    On the flag detail page, toggle it on for your target environment.
  </p>

  <h3>3. Add the SDK</h3>
  <pre><code>npm install @flick/sdk</code></pre>

  <pre><code>import {"{ FlickClient }"} from '@flick/sdk';

const flick = new FlickClient({"{"}
  baseUrl: 'https://flick-server-production.up.railway.app/api/v1',
  sdkKey: 'flk_your_sdk_key_here',
  defaultValues: {"{"} 'new-checkout': false {"}"},
{"}"});

await flick.waitForReady();

if (flick.isEnabled('new-checkout')) {"{"}
  renderNewCheckout();
{"}"}</code></pre>

  <h3>4. Get an SDK key</h3>
  <p>
    Go to <strong>Settings &gt; API Keys</strong> in the dashboard, create an <strong>SDK</strong> key,
    and bind it to your environment. The key is shown only once.
  </p>

